    "type": "SensitivityAnalysis",
    "name": "Global Sobol sensitivity analysis for hemolysis index prediction",
    "description": "A variance-based Sobol global sensitivity analysis was performed using 10,000 Monte Carlo samples drawn from the joint distribution of inlet flow rate (3–6 L/min), impeller rotational speed (2400–3200 RPM), blood viscosity (3.2–4.1 mPa·s), and the power-law hemolysis model exponents (α: 0.62–0.78, β: 0.77–0.93). The analysis identified impeller rotational speed and the hemolysis exponent α as the dominant contributors to variance in the predicted hemolysis index (first-order Sobol indices 0.41 and 0.33 respectively), with inlet flow rate contributing a first-order index of 0.18. Interaction terms accounted for the remaining 8% of total variance. These findings directed mesh refinement efforts toward high-shear impeller tip regions and constrained the experimental calibration campaign for the power-law exponents.",
    "method": "Variance-based Sobol decomposition (Saltelli et al. 2010 quasi-random sampling)",
    "dominantFactors": [
      "impeller rotational speed",
      "hemolysis power-law exponent alpha"
    ],
    "sampleSize": 10000
  },
